            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How this Alberta tax calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This Alberta tax calculator estimates your income tax using
                progressive federal and provincial tax brackets, then subtracts
                non‑refundable tax credits and adds CPP and EI contributions (if
                selected). It is inspired by official CRA tables and Alberta
                government information, but simplified for clarity.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Taxable income</h3>
              <p>
                We start from your employment income (salary or hourly wage ×
                hours × 52). The calculator assumes this is your only income and
                does not model RRSP deductions, capital gains, or business
                income.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Federal tax brackets (example 2025)</h3>
              <p>
                For illustration, the calculator uses a typical progressive
                structure similar to recent years:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <ul>
                  <li>15% on the first portion of taxable income</li>
                  <li>20.5% on the next portion</li>
                  <li>26% on the next portion</li>
                  <li>29% on the next portion</li>
                  <li>33% on income above the top threshold</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
              <p>
                Exact thresholds are updated as new CRA data becomes available.
                For planning, this level of precision is usually sufficient.
              </p>

              <h3>3. Alberta provincial tax brackets</h3>
              <p>
                Alberta also uses a progressive system. The calculator applies
                several brackets with increasing rates (e.g. 10%, 12%, 13%, 14%,
                15%) to different slices of your taxable income.
              </p>

              <h3>4. Non‑refundable tax credits</h3>
              <p>
                Non‑refundable credits reduce tax payable, but not below zero.
                The calculator includes:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Federal basic personal amount (BPA)</li>
                <li>Alberta basic personal amount</li>
                <li>
                  Optional “other” federal and Alberta credit amounts you can
                  enter
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>For each jurisdiction, tax credits are calculated as:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="text-sm">
                  <strong>Tax credits</strong> = (Basic personal amount + other
                  credit amounts) × lowest tax rate
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>5. CPP and EI contributions</h3>
              <p>If enabled, the calculator estimates:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  CPP contributions on pensionable earnings between the yearly
                  basic exemption and the maximum pensionable earnings
                </li>
                <li>
                  EI premiums on insurable earnings up to the annual maximum
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Both are capped at their yearly maximums and use the current
                contribution rates for the selected year.
              </p>

              <h3>6. Net income and paycheque amounts</h3>
              <p>
                Finally, we subtract federal tax, Alberta tax, CPP, and EI from
                your gross income to get your net (after‑tax) income. Based on
                your selected pay frequency, we divide annual amounts to show
                per‑pay figures.
              </p>

              <h2>Limitations and assumptions</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>Assumes a resident of Alberta for the entire tax year</li>
                <li>
                  Does not handle complex situations (self‑employment, rental
                  income, capital gains, stock options, etc.)
                </li>
                <li>
                  Does not include every credit (e.g. tuition, disability,
                  caregiver, dividend tax credits)
                </li>
                <li>
                  Uses rounded rates and thresholds; small differences from CRA
                  or payroll software are normal
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                For filing your return or making important financial decisions,
